Step 1:

Text Extraction

The next goal is to convert the text contained within the above Columns to data frame for ease of analysis.It is required to be converted into a collection of text documents or corpus named as corpus_review. Lets ensure that we have the Corpus for both the columns indicating these two parameters: 1) What.does.DTE.do.well.to.earn.your.satisfaction.: Earnsatisfaction 2) What.does.DTE.need.to.improve.other.than.price.to.earn.your.sat.: ImproveSatisfaction

## Make a vector source and a corpus for both the Columns containing the Customer Satisfaction Data
#Column 1: EarnSatisfaction
corpus_review1 <- Corpus(VectorSource(CustomerReview$EarnSatisfaction))

#Column 2: ImproveSatisfaction
corpus_review2 <- Corpus(VectorSource(CustomerReview$ImproveSatisfaction))

Step 2:

Text Pre-processing

In this case, we are using the Bag of Words approach for the purpose of Textual Analysis, whereby based on the frequencies of the appearence of words we could analyze the sentiment associated with certain reviews as provided by the Customer. The DTM (Document Term Matrix) can help to identify the frequency of term occuring in a collection of documents. In a DTM, rows correspond to documents in the collection and columns correspond to terms.

Both the DTM and TDM (Term Document Matrix) must be cleaned and represent the core set of relevant words, thereby necessitating the need of pre-processing activities to be performed in the corpus.

i) Conversion to Lower Case

#Converting 1st Column to Lowercase: Converting corpus_review1
corpus_review1<-tm_map(corpus_review1, tolower)
## Warning in tm_map.SimpleCorpus(corpus_review1, tolower): transformation
## drops documents
#Converting 2nd Column to Lowercase: Converting corpus_review2
corpus_review2<-tm_map(corpus_review2, tolower)
## Warning in tm_map.SimpleCorpus(corpus_review2, tolower): transformation
## drops documents

#Removing Punctuation from 1st & 2nd Column

## transformation drops documents

Step 4: Create DTM & TDM from corpus

This decides the Document Term Matrix that can help to identify the frequency of terms occuring in the corpuses. In a DTM, Rows correspond to Documents and Columns corresponds to Terms. The TDM is a transpose of DTM.

review_dtm1 <- DocumentTermMatrix(corpus_review1)
review_tdm1 <- TermDocumentMatrix(corpus_review1)

review_dtm2 <- DocumentTermMatrix(corpus_review2)
review_tdm2 <- TermDocumentMatrix(corpus_review2)

Lets use the TDM to identify the frequent terms, by converting them to matrix

# Convert TDM to matrix
review_m1 <- as.matrix(review_tdm1)
review_m2 <- as.matrix(review_tdm2)
# Sum rows and frequency data frame
review_term_freq1 <- rowSums(review_m1)
review_term_freq2 <- rowSums(review_m2)
# Sort term_frequency in descending order
review_term_freq1 <- sort(review_term_freq1, decreasing = T)
review_term_freq2 <- sort(review_term_freq2, decreasing = T)
# View the top 10 most common words
review_term_freq1[1:10]

Step 6: Comparing the Corpus

Now, that we have an idea on what all words have appeared mostly across both the survey questions, we can now deep dive to check for words that are appearing in both the two corpuses. For this purpose we need to find the commonality of words between the 2 corpuses (asking two different questions) and plot them in one shared wordcloud.

Next, we will check and compare the dissimilar words shared between the 2 corpuses.

#Taking Up each Question to Paste into a seperate Corpora
all_EarnSatisfaction <- paste(CustomerReview$EarnSatisfaction, collapse = "")
all_ImproveSatisfaction <- paste(CustomerReview$ImproveSatisfaction, collapse = "")

#Combining Corpora
all_combine <- c(all_EarnSatisfaction, all_ImproveSatisfaction)

#Creating a new Corpus for the Combined Corpuses
corpus_review_all=Corpus(VectorSource(all_combine))

Polarized Tag Plot

A polarized tag plot is an improved version of the commonality cloud. It determines the frequency of a term used in both the corpora under comparison. The difference in frequencies of common words might be insightful in many cases. For this plot, the plotrix package is loaded. First a matrix is created with all the common words using a subset to ensure that it contains only words occurring in both the classes. The matrix then has another column for the absolute difference between both the corpora for each word and the plot is made.

#Identify terms shared by both documents
common_words <- subset(all_m, all_m[, 1] > 0 & all_m[, 2] > 0)

#Calculate common words and difference
difference <- abs(common_words[, 1] - common_words[, 2])
common_words <- cbind(common_words, difference)
common_words <- common_words[order(common_words[, 3],
                                   decreasing = T), ]
head(common_words)
##         EarnSatisfaction ImproveSatisfaction difference
## help                  39                   6         33
## program               32                   8         24
## save                  30                  10         20
## effici                23                   4         19
## good                  22                   3         19
## servic                37                  19         18
#Words in Column
top6_df <- data.frame(x = common_words[1:6, 1],
                       y = common_words[1:6, 2],
                       labels = rownames(common_words[1:6, ]))
# Make pyramid plot
pyramid.plot(top6_df$x, top6_df$y,
             labels = top6_df$labels, 
             main = "Words in Common",
             gap = 10,
             laxlab = NULL,
             raxlab = NULL, 
             unit = NULL, #Can change to % by using "%" instead of NULL
             top.labels = c("EarnSatisfaction",
                            "Words",
                            "ImproveSatisfaction")
             )

Dimension Reduction using Hierarchial Clustering

By Words Clustering, we can visualize which words/group of words are used together based on their frequency distance.

review_tdm_all <- removeSparseTerms(review_tdm_all, sparse = 0.1)
review_tdm_all
## <<TermDocumentMatrix (terms: 276, documents: 2)>>
## Non-/sparse entries: 552/0
## Sparsity           : 0%
## Maximal term length: 13
## Weighting          : term frequency (tf)
hc <- hclust(d = dist((review_tdm_all), method = "euclidean"), method = "complete") #Replace method to "complete" and see the change in the Dendrogarm appearence along with change in the heights of the tree
# Plot a dendrogram
hcd = as.dendrogram(hc)
plot(hcd)

Zooming in on Dendrograms

As, we can see that the Dendrograms with all the words in both the columns are bit clumsy. Depending on the height of the tree, as we can see that the maximum height of the tree is at 40, so it would be good idea to cut the trees from the Upper and the Lower branch depending on the levels till where we can see and understand the words so used together and visualize a level of correlation between them.

#Plotting Dendrograms with some Cuts
op = par(mfrow = c(2, 1))   #decides the rows at which the visuals will be shown
plot(cut(hcd, h = 20)$upper, main = "Upper tree of cut at h=20")
plot(cut(hcd, h = 20)$lower[[4]], main = "Second branch of lower tree with cut at h=20")

Zooming in the Dendrograms after cutting at the Upper and the second branch gives an idea of the words that are being associated with each other mostly. This Cluster Diagram shows how different words are used together for expressing Customers review. The clustering is based on the frequency distances and the cluster indicates the set of words that are used most frequently together.

Zooming to the first Dendrogram

Thus, after cutting some of the branches of the trees, it gets more clear on the level of the nodes at the leaf where some of the words can be seen are used together. Such as the words servic, help, program, save are used together.

Word Associations

Lets next check the associations of each word so used in the Corpuses. This helps to identify words that appear together. Higher the correlation limit, higher are these words associations with the word so provideed within the quotations or provided as vectors.

From the results below ot looks like that even at a very low coefficient rate as low as 0.1 the association of the word help with all these other words is 1.0, indicating all these words appear together and hence the correlation is 1.

We can play with different words to see how these associations with these different keywords change.
